[[File:Obori-jinja torii.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Torii]]
'''Obori Shrine''' (おぼりじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Ishihara-chō, {{ill|lt=Takasaki|Q336438|WD=Q336438|1=Takasaki}}, {{ill|lt=Gunma Prefecture|Q129499|WD=Q129499|1=Gunma Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, the {{ill|lt=Kōzuke Province|Q1054838|WD=Q1054838|1=Kōzuke Province}}{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|lt=Nanamiya|1=Ichinomiya}}, and its former {{ill|lt=modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|lt=Gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. Its {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=shrine crest|1=UNKNOWN}} is “Mitsudomoe”{{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}.

Its old name in the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}} was “Obori Daimyōjin.”

=== Enshrined deity ===
The enshrined deity is the following one<ref>[http://www.raijin.com/obori/html/yurai/htm Origin of Obori Shrine] (official site).</ref>.
* {{ill|lt=Sukunabikona|Q3275687|WD=Q3275687|lt=Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona}}

In the '{{ill|lt=Shintōshū|Q2616931|WD=Q2616931|1=Shintōshū}},' the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=honji-butsu|1=UNKNOWN}} is {{ill|lt=Monju Bosatsu|Q471696|WD=Q471696|1=Manjushri}}{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}. However, early-modern origin records mention {{ill|lt=Yakushi Nyorai|Q854773|WD=Q854773|lt=Yakushi|1=Bhaisajyaguru}}, and a Yakushi hall also existed behind the shrine{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}. A document of {{ill|lt=1717|Q6895|WD=Q6895|1=1717}} ({{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|WD=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 2) describes the {{ill|lt=shintai|Q327532|WD=Q327532|1=Shintai}} as stone{{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}. Also, the 'Shikinaisha Survey Report' says there are 21 additional deities besides Sukunahikona-no-Mikoto{{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}.

=== History ===
=== Founding ===
Founding is unknown. Nearby is Mishimazuka Kofun (a late 4th to early 5th century {{ill|lt=round kofun|Q11394747|WD=Q11394747|1=Round Kofun}}), and early Jōmon pottery fragments were excavated from the precincts, suggesting the shrine has stood here since ancient times{{Sfn|小祝神社（神々）|1984年}}.

The clan that originally worshipped this shrine is unknown. The 'Kōzuke no Kuni Jinmyōchō' records “Sokusai-ji Obori Myōjin” in western Gunma district, and this “Sokusai-ji” is identified with {{ill|lt=Hikima Myōken-ji (Takasaki Hikima-chō)|Q11447022|WD=Q11447022|1=Myokenji Temple (Hikimacho, Takasaki City)}} near the Kōzuke provincial office. From this, the clan serving Obori deity is thought to have become provincial officials, and “Sokusai-ji Obori Myōjin” is inferred to have been invited from this shrine as ujigami to Sokusai-ji built near the provincial office{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}{{Sfn|小祝神社（平）|1987年}}{{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}.

=== Overview history ===
Founding is unknown. In the {{ill|lt=Rikkokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|lt=official national histories|1=Rikkokushi}}, there is a record that the {{ill|lt=divine rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} of “Obori-no-Kami” was promoted in {{ill|lt=880|Q23618|WD=Q23618|1=880}} ({{ill|lt=Gangyō|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 4) from Junior Fifth Rank Lower to Junior Fifth Rank Upper, rank-12 merit{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}.

In the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' '{{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}' compiled in Enchō 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}), it appears in {{ill|lt=Katōka District|Q11569784|WD=Q11569784|1=Kataoka District, Gunma}} of {{ill|lt=Kōzuke Province|Q1054838|WD=Q1054838|1=Kōzuke Province}} as “Obori Shrine,” and is listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}. The same register gives the contemporary reading as “Ohafuri”{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}.

In the 'Kōzuke no Kuni Jinmyōchō,' the Sōja text shows “Senior First Rank Obori Daimyōjin” as 7th among ten guardian shrines, while the Ichinomiya text shows it 4th, and the 'Gunsho Ruijū' text 6th, each as “Junior First Rank Obori Daimyōjin”{{Sfn|小祝神社（神々）|1984年}}. As related deity name, as noted above, “Junior Third Rank Sokusai-ji Obori Myōjin” appears in west Gunma district{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}.

In the '{{ill|lt=Shintōshū|Q2616931|WD=Q2616931|1=Shintōshū}}' compiled in the {{ill|lt=Nanboku-chō period|Q264012|WD=Q264012|1=Nanboku-chō period}}, “Jōzuke no Kuni kyūkasho daimyōjin” states “Nanamiya is Sawa-miya, called Koshi (likely mistaken for Obori), honji is Monju,” and the shrine is considered Kōzuke’s {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|lt=Nanamiya|1=Ichinomiya}}{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}}.

In the {{ill|lt=Edo period|Q184963|WD=Q184963|1=Edo period}}, it was granted Senior First Rank by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sōgen senji|1=UNKNOWN}} in {{ill|lt=1716|Q6892|WD=Q6892|1=1716}} ({{ill|lt=Shōtoku (Japan)|Q1193848|WD=Q1193848|lt=Shōtoku|1=Shōtoku (era)}} 6){{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}. In {{ill|lt=1717|Q6895|WD=Q6895|1=1717}} (Kyōhō 2), the current main sanctuary was built{{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}. The {{ill|lt=early-modern|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}} {{ill|lt=bettō temple|Q11396755|WD=Q11396755|1=Bettō-ji}} was Sekishō-ji{{Sfn|中世諸国一宮制|2000年|p=282}} (still adjacent today).

In {{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}} (Meiji 5), it was ranked {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Gōsha|1=UNKNOWN}} under the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=modern shrine rank system|1=UNKNOWN}}, and in {{ill|lt=1909|Q2057|WD=Q2057|1=1909}} (Meiji 42), it was designated as a shrine receiving offerings of sacred food and cloth{{Sfn|小祝神社（式内社）|1986年}}.

